{{use British English|date=September 2017}} {{use DMY dates|date=September 2017}} {{Infobox military unit |unit_name = No. 100 Group RAF |image = |caption = |dates = 1943–1945 |country = [[United Kingdom]] |branch = [[Royal Air Force]] |command_structure = [[RAF Bomber Command]] |type = |role = Electronic countermeasures |size = |current_commander = |garrison = |garrison_label = |ceremonial_chief = |ceremonial_chief_label = |colonel_of_the_regiment = |colonel_of_the_regiment_label = |nickname = |motto = Confound and Destroy<ref>{{cite book|last1=Pine|first1=L.G.|title=A dictionary of mottoes|date=1983|publisher=Routledge & Kegan Paul|location=London|isbn=0-7100-9339-X|page=37|edition=1}}</ref> |colors = [[Image:Ensign of the Royal Air Force.svg|125px]] |colors_label = [[Royal Air Force Ensign]] |march = |mascot = |equipment = |notable_commanders =[[Edward Addison]] |identification_symbol = |identification_symbol_label = |anniversaries = <!-- Aircraft --> |aircraft_electronic=[[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress]], [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator]], [[Handley Page Halifax]], [[Short Stirling]], [[Vickers Wellington]] |aircraft_fighter= [[Bristol Beaufighter]], [[de Havilland Mosquito]] }}
'''No. 100 (Bomber Support) Group''' was a special duties [[Group (air force)|group]] within [[RAF]] [[RAF Bomber Command|Bomber Command]]. The group was formed on 11 November 1943 to consolidate the increasingly complex business of [[electronic warfare]] and [[Electronic countermeasures|countermeasure]]s in one organisation. The group was responsible for the development, operational trial and use of electronic warfare and countermeasures equipment. It was based at RAF stations in [[East Anglia]], chiefly [[Norfolk]].
The group was a pioneer in countering the formidable force of [[radar]]-equipped [[Luftwaffe]] [[night fighter]]s, using a range of [[Electromagnetic spectrum|electronic]] 'homers' fitted to [[de Havilland Mosquito]] fighters which detected night fighter radar and radio emissions and allowed the RAF fighters to home in onto the [[Axis powers|Axis]] aircraft and either shoot them down or disrupt their missions against the [[bomber stream]]s. Other Mosquitoes would patrol around Luftwaffe fighter airfields ready to attack night fighters as they landed.
This constant harassment had a detrimental effect on the morale and confidence of many Luftwaffe crews and indirectly led to a high proportion of aircraft and aircrew wastage from crashes as night fighters hurried in to land to avoid the Mosquito threat (real or imagined). {{Citation needed|date=December 2008}}
From 1944–45, the Mosquitos of 100 Group claimed 258 Luftwaffe aircraft shot down for 70 losses. The gradually increasing threat from the RAF fighters also created what the Luftwaffe crews nicknamed ''Moskito Panik'' as the night fighter crews were never sure when or where they may come under attack from the marauding 100 Group fighters.
[[File:Lancaster I NG128 Dropping Load - Duisburg - Oct 14 - 1944.jpg|thumb|A Lancaster with [[List of World War II electronic warfare equipment|Airborne Cigar]] (ABC) radio jamming equipment - the two vertical [[Antenna (radio)|aerials]] on the fuselage]] Top Mosquito ace with 100 Group was [[Wing Commander (rank)|Wing Commander]] [[Branse Burbridge]] of [[No. 85 Squadron RAF|85 Squadron]], with 21 claims from 1944–45.
The bomber squadrons of 100 Group utilised various specialist electronic jamming devices to disrupt German [[Radio|radio communications]] and radar. During 100 Group's existence over 32 different devices were evaluated and used. Specially equipped 100 Group aircraft would fly in the bomber stream. Much of this equipment was developed at the [[Telecommunications Research Establishment]] (TRE).
Special equipment used included ''Airborne Cigar'' (ABC) jammer, ''Jostle'' (jammer), ''Mandrel'' (jammer), ''Airborne Grocer'' (jammer), ''Piperack'' (jammer), ''[[Perfectos]]'' (homer), ''[[Serrate radar detector|Serrate]]'' (homer), ''Corona'' (spoofer), ''Carpet'' (jammer) and ''Lucero'' (homer), used against German equipment such as [[Lichtenstein radar|''Lichtenstein'']], [[Freya radar|''Freya'']], and [[Würzburg radar|''Wurzburg'']] radars.
{{cquote|The combination of the [[Pathfinder (RAF)|Pathfinders]]' operations, the activities of No. 100 Group, the British advantage in radar, jamming and [[Chaff (radar countermeasure)|Window]] techniques, combined with intelligent attacking tactics, as well as the discipline and bravery of the RAF crews, have been remarkable. We had our'' (sic) ''severe problems in trying to defend Germany in the air |4=''General der Jagdflieger'', [[Adolf Galland]]. |5=Lancaster - the Biography{{sfn|Iveson|Milton|2009|p=122}}}}
==Order of battle== [[File:Boeing Fortress ECM aircraft 214 Sqn RAF at Prestwick 1944.jpg|thumb|An electronic warfare Fortress III of [[No. 214 Squadron RAF|214 Squadron]] with nose-mounted [[H2S (radar)|H2S]] [[radome]]]] No. 100 Group was headquartered at [[Bylaugh Hall]], [[Norfolk]] from January 1944, a central location from which to administer the group's airfields in north Norfolk. No 100 Group operated from eight airfields with approximately 260 aircraft, 140 of which were various marks of Mosquito night fighter intruders with the remainder consisting of [[Handley Page Halifax]]es, [[Short Stirling]]s, [[Vickers Wellington]]s, [[Boeing B-17 Flying Fortress|Fortresses]] and [[Consolidated B-24 Liberator|Liberators]] carrying electronic jamming equipment. The group also operated the [[Bristol Beaufighter]] for a short time.
The group disbanded on 17 December 1945. During its existence it had one commander, [[Air Vice-Marshal]] [[Edward Addison]].
