{{POV|date=January 2016}}
'''SmarterChild''' was a [[chatbot]] available on [[AOL Instant Messenger]] and [[Windows Live Messenger]] (previously [[MSN Messenger]]) networks.{{cn|date=September 2013}}

==History==
SmarterChild was an intelligent agent or bot developed by [[ActiveBuddy]], Inc., with offices in New York and Sunnyvale.{{where?|date=May 2018}}{{cn|date=September 2013}} It was widely distributed across global instant messaging and [[SMS]] networks.{{cn|date=September 2013}}

Founded in 2000, ActiveBuddy was the brainchild of [[Robert Hoffer]], Timothy Kay and Peter Levitan. The idea for instant messaging bots came from the team's vision to add natural language comprehension functionality to the increasingly popular instant messaging and SMS platforms.{{cn|date=September 2013}} The original implementation took shape as a word-based adventure game but quickly grew to include a wide range of database applications including instant access to news, weather, stock information, movie times, yellow pages listings, and detailed sports data, as well as a variety of tools (personal assistant, calculators, translator, etc.).{{cn|date=September 2013}} The company had not launched a public bot until the arrival of the eventual new-CEO, Stephen Klein.  Shortly after he arrived at the company in May 2001, he insisted that all of the knowledge domains (sports, weather, movies, etc.) plus the chat functionality be bundled together and launched under the screen name "SmarterChild" which was one of the many test bots that were being run internally (the screen name "SmarterChild" was one of Timothy Kay's personal test bots). The bundled domains were launched publicly as SmarterChild (on [[AOL Instant Messenger]] initially) in June 2001.{{cn|date=September 2013}} SmarterChild acted as a showcase for the quick data access and possibilities for fun personalized conversation that the company planned to turn into customized, niche specific products.{{cn|date=September 2013}}

The rapid success of SmarterChild led to targeted marketing-oriented bots for [[Radiohead]], [[Austin Powers (film series)|Austin Powers]], [[Intel]], [[Keebler]], ''[[The Sporting News]]'' and others.{{cn|date=September 2013}} ActiveBuddy strengthened its hold on the intelligent agent market by receiving a U.S. patent in 2002.<ref>https://encrypted.google.com/patents/EP1767015A1?cl=da</ref>{{cn|date=September 2013}}

ActiveBuddy changed its name to Colloquis and prospered selling a superior automated customer service SAS offering to large companies (including [[Comcast]], [[Time Warner]], [[Cingular]] and [[Vonage]] among others). [[Microsoft]] acquired Colloquis in 2007 and proceeded to decommission SmarterChild and discontinue the Automated Service Agent business as well.{{cn|date=September 2017}}

