<!-- Deleted image removed: [[File:Drones for Good Award Logo.png|thumb|Drones for Good Award]] --> '''UAE Drones for Good''' is an annual international competition and award by the [[Government of the United Arab Emirates|government]] of the [[United Arab Emirates]] to encourage useful and positive applications for [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|drone]] technology. The largest of its kind, the award currently stands at $1 million for the international competition and UAE Dhs1 million for the UAE competition.<ref>{{Cite web|title = UAE Drones for Good Award: Wadi Drone makes conservationists’ job easier|url = http://gulfnews.com/news/uae/government/uae-drones-for-good-award-wadi-drone-makes-conservationists-job-easier-1.1452917|website = gulfnews.com|accessdate = 2015-05-24}}</ref>
The award was launched at the UAE Government Summit 2014.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Drones for Good: UAE Honors Peaceful-Purpose Innovators|url = http://www.huffingtonpost.com/faisal-abbas/drones-for-good-uae-honor_b_6640152.html|website = The Huffington Post|accessdate = 2015-05-24}}</ref> The first 2015 award was contested by more than 800 entries from 57 countries including [[Massachusetts Institute of Technology|MIT's]] 'Waterfly' collaborative drone 'swarms'.<ref>{{Cite web|title = MIT’s entry in Dubai’s ‘Drones For Good’ contest is a drone swarm that can land on water|url = http://www.betaboston.com/news/2015/02/02/mits-entry-in-dubais-drones-for-good-contest-is-a-drone-swarm-that-can-land-on-water/|accessdate = 2015-05-24}}</ref><ref>{{Cite web|title = Drones For Good Gives UAVs A Reputation Overhaul|url = http://www.entrepreneur.com/article/243729|accessdate = 2015-05-24|first = Pamella|last = Leon}}</ref> The finalists included Spanish company [[CATUAV]] for a drone fitted with optical sensors to scan war-affected regions of [[Bosnia and Herzegovina]] for [[Land mine|landmines]] buried during the 1990s.<ref name="newatlas">{{cite web|last1=Lavars|first1=Nick|title=Imaging drones to spot signs of explosive chemicals leaking from landmines|url=http://newatlas.com/drones-landmines-bristol/42732/|publisher=New Atlas|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><!--aerial photographs from the drone are run through a post-processing programme that provides a mosaic map of the area and determines the probability of landmines.-->.<ref>{{cite web|last1=Wasmi|first1=Naser Al|title=UAE entrants offer positive alternatives uses for drones in competition|url=http://www.thenational.ae/uae/technology/uae-entrants-offer-positive-alternatives-uses-for-drones-in-competition|publisher=The National|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Adams|first1=Derek|title=Drones for Good awards to give $1 million to UAVs that do things other than killing and spying|url=http://www.t3.com/news/drones-for-good-awards|publisher=T3|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|last1=Kennedy|first1=David|title=How these drones for disaster relief and eliminating landmines are aiming to rebrand the controversial technology|url=http://business.financialpost.com/fp-tech-desk/how-these-drones-for-disaster-relief-and-eliminating-landmines-are-aiming-to-rebrand-the-controversial-technology?__lsa=0180-ebbe|publisher=Financial Post|accessdate=20 December 2016}}</ref> The eventual winner was a Swiss company with their search and rescue Gimball drone.<ref>{{Cite web|title = Swiss search-and-rescue drone wins UAE competition {{!}} The National|url = http://www.thenational.ae/uae/science/swiss-search-and-rescue-drone-wins-uae-competition|accessdate = 2015-05-24}}</ref>
The 2016 competition awarded Loon Copter's sea-hybrid [[Unmanned aerial vehicle|UAV]] in February 2017.<ref>{{Cite web|title = US$ 2 Million 'UAE Drones for Good Award' and 'UAE AI & Robotics Award for Good' Declare Winners|url = http://www.prnewswire.com/news-releases/us-2-million-uae-drones-for-good-award-and-uae-ai--robotics-award-for-good-declare-winners-567927981.html|website = www.prnewswire.com|access-date = 11 February 2016|first = Dubai Museum of the Future|last = Foundation}}</ref>
